#compdef smartthings
# =============================================================================
# smartthings — SmartThings Community's "Command Line Interface
#               for the SmartThings APIs" — Samsung SmartThings'
#               official Node.js CLI for managing devices, apps,
#               rules, scenes, locations, and Edge drivers in the
#               SmartThings home-automation ecosystem.
#               Distinguishing from Home Assistant's CLI, OpenHAB's
#               karaf shell, ESPHome's CLI, and other home-
#               automation management tools by:
#                 - 18 TOP-LEVEL COMMAND GROUPS covering apps,
#                   capabilities, config, devicepreferences,
#                   deviceprofiles, devices, edge, installedapps,
#                   installedschema, locations, organizations,
#                   presentation, rules, scenes, schema,
#                   virtualdevices + login/logout
#                 - YARGS-BASED COMMAND TREE with rich per-
#                   subcommand options (filter by AppType /
#                   AppClassification, output format yaml/json/
#                   table, paginated list views with id-or-index)
#                 - DUAL OUTPUT MODES: outputItemOrList helper
#                   shows TABLE format by default with --output
#                   flag for yaml/json, suitable for both human
#                   browsing + automation pipelines
#                 - EDGE DRIVER DEVELOPMENT: `smartthings edge`
#                   subcommand tree for building/uploading/
#                   debugging Lua-based Edge drivers (which run
#                   ON-DEVICE at the SmartThings hub)
#                 - API AUTHENTICATION via OAuth or Personal
#                   Access Token; logout subcommand clears creds
#                 - CONFIG FILE: ~/.config/@smartthings/cli/
#                   config.yaml stores profile settings
#                 - log4js STRUCTURED LOGGING: every log call
#                   routed through log4js.getLogger(name) with
#                   per-category log levels + multiple appender
#                   support (Console, File, RollingFile, etc.)
#               Used by: SmartThings device manufacturers + Edge
#               driver developers + power users automating home
#               environments + integrators connecting SmartThings
#               to other home-automation ecosystems.
#
# Author:  SmartThings Inc. (Samsung SmartThings — acquired by
#          Samsung in 2014).  @smartthings/cli npm package
#          released ~2020; continuously developed by
#          SmartThingsCommunity organization on GitHub through
#          2026 with quarterly releases (currently v2.1.x).
# Source:  https://github.com/SmartThingsCommunity/smartthings-cli
#          https://github.com/SmartThingsCommunity/smartthings-cli/blob/main/src/run.ts
#          https://github.com/SmartThingsCommunity/smartthings-cli/blob/main/src/commands/*.ts
#          https://github.com/SmartThingsCommunity/smartthings-cli/blob/main/src/lib/io-util.ts
# CLI:     src/run.ts → buildInstance(commands).parse() — uses
#          yargs 18.x with command modules per subcommand;
#          src/commands/*.ts defines one yargs CommandModule per
#          top-level command group with builder() that adds
#          positionals + options.  Headline library: **log4js**
#          (yargs is well-documented; log4js is the new variant
#          being documented here).
# Library: log4js (https://github.com/log4js-node/log4js-node)
#          ("log4js-node" — Stuart Sierra (original 2011) →
#           Gareth Jones (2013+ maintainer, log4js-node org) —
#           released 2011 as a Node.js port of Java's log4j
#           framework.  Distinct from winston (R580), pino
#           (R584), debug (R592), consola (R576), roarr (R604)
#           by being the FAITHFUL Java-log4j PORT for Node:
#             1. APPENDER / CATEGORY / LEVEL ARCHITECTURE
#                matching log4j semantics: appenders are
#                output destinations (console/file/rolling/
#                stream/etc.), categories are logger names
#                (hierarchical: "app.module.submodule"), and
#                levels are trace/debug/info/warn/error/fatal/
#                mark/off
#             2. log4js.configure({ appenders, categories })
#                — entire config as a JSON object (loaded from
#                file or inline) with appender definitions +
#                category-level mappings
#             3. log4js.getLogger(category) — retrieve a named
#                logger; categories form a hierarchy where
#                child categories inherit parent config unless
#                overridden
#             4. APPENDER ECOSYSTEM — 12+ built-in appenders:
#                console, stdout, stderr, file, dateFile (date-
#                rotating files), gelf (Graylog), logFaces-UDP,
#                logFaces-HTTP, multiprocess, recording (test
#                helper), smtp, slack
#             5. LEVEL THRESHOLDS PER CATEGORY — different
#                modules can have different log levels:
#                "app.network.client" can be at DEBUG while
#                "app.db" is at WARN
#             6. LAYOUT FUNCTIONS — output formatting via Layout
#                functions (basic / colored / messagePassThrough
#                / dummy / pattern / custom)
#             7. FAITHFUL log4j PATTERN LAYOUT — `%c %p [%d] %m`
#                style format strings matching log4j 1.x exactly
#                — Java developers find the API immediately
#                familiar)
