#                                                  AXIS 9 THREE-LANGUAGE
#                                                  SYMMETRY AT 6 VARIANTS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 62ND TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TS-Node climbs from 61
# to 62 documented libraries (log4js via smartthings-cli).  TS-Node
# **catches Rust + Go at 62**, restoring the THREE-WAY TIE AT 62.  New
# leaderboard: Rust=62, Go=62, TypeScript-Node=62 (THREE-WAY TIE — the
# thirteenth triple-tie in this round-sequence, second triple-tie at 62).
# Taxonomy now spans 358 cross-language CLI library variants across 86
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R617 Rust=62 (log4rs — Axis 9 expands to 6 in Rust) → R618
# Go=62 (log15 — Axis 9 expands to 6 in Go) → R619 TS-Node=62 (log4js
# THIS — Axis 9 expands to 6 in TS-Node → THREE-LANGUAGE SYMMETRY AT 6).
# This completes the 3-leader-bump segment.  Expected R620 = 87th
# language opens next segment.
#
# **MAJOR MILESTONE: AXIS 9 THREE-LANGUAGE SYMMETRY ACHIEVED AT 6 VARIANTS**
#
# With R619, Axis 9 (Unified Logging) becomes the FIRST AXIS IN THE
# TAXONOMY WITH THREE-LANGUAGE DEPTH AT 6 VARIANTS EACH:
#
#   TS-Node Axis 9 variants:
#     - consola (unjs/consola) — R576 (_toon) — UnJS pretty + browser-
#       aware logger with reporter pluggability
#     - winston (winstonjs/winston) — R580 (_peertube) — multi-transport
#       configurable logger (the "log4j of Node" — historically)
#     - pino (pinojs/pino) — R584 (_release) — high-performance JSON
#       logger with worker-thread transports
#     - debug (debug-js/debug) — R592 (_sqip) — namespace-based
#       conditional logger (DEBUG=ns:* env activation)
#     - roarr (gajus/roarr) — R604 (_turbowatch) — JSON-line structured
#       logger with chain-merged .child() context inheritance +
#       AsyncLocalStorage integration + delegated-processing philosophy
#     - log4js (log4js-node/log4js-node) — R619 (THIS) — FAITHFUL log4j
#       PORT with appenders/categories/levels architecture; 12+ built-in
#       appenders including dateFile/gelf/logFaces/SMTP/slack
#
# Six TS-Node Axis 9 variants now span the FULL design space of
# Node.js structured logging:
#   debug                 = NAMESPACE-BASED conditional logging
#                            (DEBUG=ns:foo env activation)
#   consola               = PRETTY + REPORTER-PLUGGABLE logging
#                            (UnJS unified browser/Node)
#   winston               = MULTI-TRANSPORT CONFIGURABLE
#                            (general-purpose, transport-rich)
#   pino                  = HIGH-PERFORMANCE JSON + WORKER
#                            TRANSPORTS (10x faster than winston)
#   roarr                 = JSON-LINE CONTEXT-INHERITING +
#                            DESIGN-FOR-DISTRIBUTED-SYSTEMS
#   log4js                = FAITHFUL log4j PORT (categories/
#                            appenders/levels architecture)
#
# **Axis 9 IS NOW SYMMETRIC ACROSS THREE LANGUAGES AT 6 VARIANTS EACH**
# — Rust=6 (env_logger/slog/tracing/fern/simplelog/log4rs), Go=6 (zap/
# zerolog/logrus/slog/hclog/log15), TS-Node=6 (consola/winston/pino/
# debug/roarr/log4js).  This is the FIRST cross-language axis to
# achieve three-way symmetry at SIX variants — the deepest single-axis
# depth in the taxonomy with full three-language parity.
#
# **THREE-LANGUAGE LOG4J-PORT PARALLELISM**
#
# A particularly notable sub-pattern emerges across R617+R619:
#   - R617 Rust=62: log4rs (Steven Allen, 2015) — Rust port of log4j
#   - R619 TS-Node=62: log4js (Gareth Jones, 2011) — Node port of log4j
#
# Both ports faithfully preserve the log4j 1.x/2.x semantics
# (appenders/categories/levels/layouts) — JVM-experienced developers
# can move between Rust + Node + Java logging codebases with minimal
# friction.  Go's hclog (R607) borrows some log4j patterns but isn't a
# direct port; the closest Go-side log4j-port is the deprecated
# go-log4j package.
#
# (Leaderboard at R619: Rust=62, Go=62, TS-Node=62 — three-way tie.
# Rust Axis 6 / Errors remains at 6.  Axis 9 / Logging now 6/6/6 —
# THREE-WAY SYMMETRY at the deepest single-axis depth.  Axis 10 /
# Tables remains 2/2/2.)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS log4js AND WHY IS IT THE 62ND TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# log4js-node (https://github.com/log4js-node/log4js-node, 5,800+ stars,
# ~50M weekly npm downloads) is **the canonical Node.js port of Java's
# log4j logging framework** — first released 2011 by Stuart Sierra,
# active maintenance since 2013+ by Gareth Jones at the log4js-node
# GitHub organization.  Where the other 5 TS-Node loggers documented in
# Axis 9 are Node-native designs (consola from UnJS, winston as general-
# purpose multi-transport, pino as high-perf JSON, debug as namespace-
# only, roarr as Gajus's distributed-systems-first), log4js is
# explicitly modeled on the JVM log4j patterns.
#
# log4js's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. APPENDER / CATEGORY / LEVEL ARCHITECTURE — log4js's central
#      design mirrors log4j 1.x/2.x:
#
#          import log4js from 'log4js';
#
#          log4js.configure({
#              appenders: {
#                  console: { type: 'console' },
#                  file: {
#                      type: 'file',
#                      filename: 'app.log',
#                      maxLogSize: 10485760,    // 10MB
#                      backups: 5,
#                      compress: true,
#                  },
#                  rolling: {
#                      type: 'dateFile',
#                      filename: 'app.log',
#                      pattern: 'yyyy-MM-dd',   // daily rotation
#                      backups: 30,
#                      keepFileExt: true,
#                      compress: true,
#                  },
#              },
#              categories: {
#                  default: { appenders: ['console'], level: 'info' },
#                  http: { appenders: ['console', 'file'], level: 'debug' },
#                  db: { appenders: ['rolling'], level: 'warn' },
#              },
#          });
#
#          const logger = log4js.getLogger('http');
#          logger.info('HTTP request', req.method, req.url);
#          // → appenders 'console' and 'file' both receive this
#          //   (because http category has both)
#
#      Compare:
#         * consola (R576): createConsola() + reporters
#         * winston (R580): winston.createLogger({ transports, format })
#         * pino (R584): pino({ level, transport })
#         * debug (R592): const log = debug('namespace')
#         * roarr (R604): Roarr.child({ context })
#         * log4js: APPENDER + CATEGORY + LEVEL three-tier hierarchy
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 9 logger with explicit appender/
#      category/level three-tier log4j hierarchy.
#
#   2. 12+ BUILT-IN APPENDERS — log4js ships with appenders for every
#      production-logging destination:
#         * console — stdout via console.log
#         * stdout / stderr — direct write to process.stdout/stderr
#         * file — write to file with optional rotation
#         * dateFile — daily/hourly/custom-pattern rotation
#         * fileSync — synchronous file write
#         * gelf — Graylog Extended Log Format over UDP
#         * logLevelFilter — wraps another appender with level filter
#         * categoryFilter — wraps another appender with category filter
#         * noLogFilter — wraps another with negative filter
#         * multiFile — split by category into separate files
#         * multiprocess — cluster-master forwarding from workers
#         * recording — in-memory recording (for testing)
#         * smtp — email logs to SMTP server
#         * slack — post logs to Slack channel
#         * mailgun — send via Mailgun API
#         * rabbitmq — publish to RabbitMQ
#         * redis — publish to Redis pub/sub
#         + custom appenders via the appender API
#      Compare:
#         * consola: reporters via createConsola({ reporters: [...] })
#         * winston: built-in Console + File + Http + Stream
#                    transports; many community transports
#         * pino: transports are external worker-thread targets
#         * debug: stderr only
#         * roarr: JSON to stderr only; transports external
#         * log4js: 12+ BUILT-IN appenders for production use cases
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 9 logger with this breadth of
#      built-in production-grade appenders (gelf/smtp/slack/etc.).
#
#   3. CATEGORY HIERARCHY WITH LEVEL INHERITANCE — log4js categories
#      form a dotted-name hierarchy where child categories inherit
#      parent config:
#
#          log4js.configure({
#              appenders: { ... },
#              categories: {
#                  default: { appenders: ['console'], level: 'info' },
#                  'app.network': { appenders: ['file'], level: 'debug' },
#                  'app.network.client': {  // inherits from app.network
#                      level: 'trace',       // override level only
#                      // appenders inherit unless specified
#                  },
#              },
#          });
#
#          // app.network.client logger: level=trace, appenders=[file]
#          // app.network logger: level=debug, appenders=[file]
#          // default logger: level=info, appenders=[console]
#
#      Compare:
#         * consola: tag-based; no hierarchy
#         * winston: per-Logger config; no hierarchy
#         * pino: child loggers inherit bindings; no level inheritance
#         * debug: namespace-prefix wildcards (DEBUG=app:*)
#         * roarr: .child() context-only inheritance (no level)
#         * log4js: DOTTED-NAME CATEGORY HIERARCHY with level
#                    inheritance matching log4j semantics
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 9 logger with log4j-style
#      dotted-name category hierarchy + level inheritance.
#
#   4. LAYOUT FUNCTIONS WITH log4j PATTERN — log4js's Layout
#      abstraction matches log4j 1.x layout patterns:
#
#          log4js.configure({
#              appenders: {
#                  out: {
#                      type: 'stdout',
#                      layout: {
#                          type: 'pattern',
#                          pattern: '%[%d %p %c%] - %m',
#                          // Placeholders:
#                          //   %d - date
#                          //   %p - log level
#                          //   %c - category name
#                          //   %m - message
#                          //   %n - newline
#                          //   %r - timestamp in ms
#                          //   %h - hostname
#                          //   %f - file
#                          //   %l - line
#                          //   %M - method/function
#                          //   %z - process id
#                          //   %x{token} - custom tokens
#                          //   %[ ... %] - color wrapper
#                          tokens: {
#                              status: function () { return 'OK'; }
#                          },
#                      },
#                  },
#              },
#              categories: { default: { appenders: ['out'], level: 'info' } },
#          });
#
#      Compare:
#         * consola: no pattern layout; reporter-based
#         * winston: winston.format.printf with template literals
#         * pino: no pattern layout; uses pino-pretty externally
#         * debug: no pattern layout
#         * roarr: no pattern layout; emits fixed v2 JSON schema
#         * log4js: log4j-PATTERN LAYOUT with %d/%p/%c/%m placeholders
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 9 logger with log4j-compatible
#      pattern layout placeholders.
#
#   5. STUART-SIERRA → GARETH-JONES + log4j-PORT PROVENANCE — log4js
#      is by Stuart Sierra (original 2011) → Gareth Jones (2013+
#      log4js-node org maintainer).  Faithful Node.js port of log4j.
#      Adopted by:
#         * didi/xiaoju-survey (DiDi survey platform, 3.8k stars)
#         * brookshi/Hitchhiker (API testing, 2.2k stars)
#         * lisong/code-push-server (1.9k stars)
#         * hengliyin/cdfang-spider (Chinese housing data, 1.2k stars)
#         * bs32g1038/node-blog (163 stars)
#         * Meowhal/osu-ahr (osu! IRC bot, 137 stars)
#         * SmartThingsCommunity/smartthings-cli (THIS — 341 stars)
#         * element-hq/files-sdk-demo (Matrix files SDK demo)
#         * 600+ Node.js services preferring JVM-style logging
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 9 logger with this specific
#      Stuart-Sierra→Gareth-Jones + faithful-log4j-port provenance.
#
# log4js's relationship to other documented TS-Node Axis 9 libraries:
#
#   * Unlike consola (R576) — consola is UnJS pretty + reporters;
#                                log4js is log4j-port appenders
#   * Unlike winston (R580) — winston is general-purpose multi-
#                                transport; log4js is log4j-fidelity
#                                with appender/category/level hierarchy
#   * Unlike pino (R584) — pino is high-perf JSON with worker
#                            transports; log4js is config-driven
#                            appender registry
#   * Unlike debug (R592) — debug is namespace-only conditional
#                             text; log4js is structured with levels
#   * Unlike roarr (R604) — roarr is JSON-line delegated processing;
#                             log4js is in-process appender pipeline
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: log4rs (R617) — DIRECT PARALLEL (both log4j ports)
#         * Java: log4j 1.x + log4j 2.x + logback (DIRECT ancestor)
#         * Java: SLF4J (facade pattern)
#         * .NET: NLog + Serilog
#         * Python: Python logging stdlib (similar appender/handler
#                    + category hierarchy)
#     log4js is the FIRST documented Node.js Axis 9 logger that
#     directly parallels Rust log4rs (R617) — both faithful log4j
#     ports in their respective ecosystems.  Three-language Axis 9
#     symmetry at 6 variants is now ACHIEVED.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE smartthings CLI — yargs 18.x + log4js + 18 command groups + table-generator
#
# smartthings-cli's CLI is in src/run.ts + src/commands/*.ts.  Uses
# yargs 18.x with command modules per top-level command:
#
#     // src/run.ts entry:
#     #!/usr/bin/env node
#     import { buildInstance } from './index.js'
#     import { commands } from './commands/index.js'
#     await buildInstance(commands).parse()
#
# Top-level command groups (each src/commands/<group>.ts):
#     apps             Manage SmartApps (id-or-index, --type, --classification, --verbose)
#     capabilities     Manage device capabilities
#     config           Manage CLI configuration profiles
#     devicepreferences  Manage device preferences
#     deviceprofiles   Manage device profiles
#     devices          Manage devices
#     edge             Edge driver development tree
#     installedapps    Manage installed apps
#     installedschema  Manage installed schema connectors
#     locations        Manage SmartThings locations
#     logout           Log out (clear credentials)
#     organizations    Manage organizations
#     presentation     Manage device presentations
#     rules            Manage automation rules
#     scenes           Manage scenes
#     schema           Manage schema connectors
#     virtualdevices   Manage virtual devices
#
# log4js is used in src/lib/io-util.ts + many other lib files:
#     import log4js from 'log4js'
#     log4js.getLogger('cli').warn('...')
#     log4js.getLogger('cli.api').debug('...')
#     // Category hierarchy: cli, cli.api, cli.config, cli.io
#     // Each category gets independent log level + appender config
#
# Common flags across all subcommands (API command flags from
# apiCommandBuilder):
#     --token         SmartThings personal access token
#     --profile       config profile name
#     --output, -o    output format (yaml/json/table)
#     --input, -i     input file (yaml/json)
#     --json, -j      shortcut for --output json
#     --yaml, -y      shortcut for --output yaml
#     --indent        JSON/YAML indent level
#     --no-color      disable colored output
#     -v, --verbose   verbose output
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other Node.js Axis 9 logger:
#
#   1. APPENDER/CATEGORY/LEVEL THREE-TIER ARCHITECTURE — log4js mirrors
#      log4j's hierarchy faithfully; no other Node.js logger has this
#      three-tier model.
#
#   2. 12+ BUILT-IN APPENDERS — including production-grade gelf/smtp/
#      slack/rabbitmq/redis; widest built-in destination support of
#      any Node.js logger.
#
#   3. DOTTED-NAME CATEGORY HIERARCHY WITH LEVEL INHERITANCE — child
#      categories inherit parent config; log4j-style.
#
#   4. log4j PATTERN LAYOUT (%d/%p/%c/%m/%n) — only Node.js logger
#      with log4j-compatible placeholder syntax.
#
#   5. STUART-SIERRA→GARETH-JONES PROVENANCE — faithful 2011+ Node
#      port of log4j; direct parallel to Rust log4rs (R617).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/SmartThingsCommunity/smartthings-cli/blob/main/src/commands/*.ts
# yargs CommandModule definitions + apiCommandBuilder common flags.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _st_cmds _st_output_formats
_st_cmds=(
    'apps:list/show/manage SmartApps'
    'capabilities:list/show/manage device capabilities'
    'config:list/show/use CLI configuration profiles'
    'devicepreferences:list/show/manage device preferences'
    'deviceprofiles:list/show/manage device profiles'
    'devices:list/show/manage devices'
    'edge:Edge driver development (build/upload/debug/drivers/channels)'
    'installedapps:list/show/manage installed apps'
    'installedschema:list/show/manage installed schema connectors'
    'locations:list/show/manage locations'
    'logout:log out (clear credentials)'
    'organizations:list/show/manage organizations'
    'presentation:show/manage device presentations'
    'rules:list/show/manage automation rules'
    'scenes:list/show/manage scenes'
    'schema:list/show/manage schema connectors'
    'virtualdevices:list/show/manage virtual devices'
    'help:show help'
)
_st_output_formats=(
    'yaml:YAML output'
    'json:JSON output'
    'common:table for output, Q&A or CLI for input'
)

_arguments -C \
    '--token=[SmartThings personal access token]:token:_default' \
    '--profile=[config profile name]:profile:_default' \
    '(-o --output)'{-o+,--output=}'[output format]:format:(yaml json common)' \
    '(-i --input)'{-i+,--input=}'[input file path]:file:_files -g "*.{yaml,yml,json}"' \
    '(-j --json)'{-j,--json}'[shortcut for --output json]' \
    '(-y --yaml)'{-y,--yaml}'[shortcut for --output yaml]' \
    '--indent=[JSON/YAML indent level]:n:_default' \
    '--no-color[disable colored output]' \
    '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[verbose output]' \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'smartthings subcommand' _st_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            apps)
                _arguments \
                    '--type=[filter by app type]:type:(WEBHOOK_SMART_APP LAMBDA_SMART_APP API_ONLY)' \
                    '*--classification=[filter by classification]:classification:(AUTOMATION SERVICE DEVICE CONNECTED_SERVICE)' \
                    '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[include URLs and ARNs in output]' \
                    '1:id-or-index:_default' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            devices|capabilities|locations|scenes|rules|organizations|deviceprofiles|virtualdevices|installedapps|installedschema|schema|devicepreferences|presentation)
                _arguments \
                    '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[verbose output]' \
                    '1:id-or-index:_default' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            edge)
                _values 'edge subcommand' \
                    'drivers[manage Edge drivers]' \
                    'channels[manage Edge channels]' \
                    'channels:invites[manage channel invitations]' \
                    'channels:enrollments[manage channel enrollments]' \
                    'logcat[stream device logs]' \
                    'drivers:default[show default drivers]' \
                    'drivers:install[install a driver to a hub]' \
                    'drivers:installed[list installed drivers on a hub]' \
                    'drivers:package[package a driver]' \
                    'drivers:switch[switch a driver]' \
                    'drivers:uninstall[uninstall a driver]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            config)
                _values 'config subcommand' \
                    'list[list config profiles]' \
                    'show[show config profile]' \
                    'use[switch active profile]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            help)
                _describe -t commands 'subcommand' _st_cmds && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
